para.verbatim: Internal API to disable automatic discovery

Internal API to disregard ext_modules.
Normally auto-discovery would not be triggered if ``ext_modules`` are set (this is done for backward compatibility with existing packages relying on ``setup.py`` or ``setup.cfg``). However, ``setuptools`` can call this function to ignore given ``ext_modules`` and proceed with the auto-discovery if ``packages`` and ``py_modules`` are not given (e.g. when using pyproject.toml metadata).
``True`` if the user has specified some form of package/module listing
The user can explicitly give a package layout via ``package_dir``

Try to find all packages or modules under the ``src`` directory (or anything pointed by ``package_dir[""]``).
The "src-layout" is relatively safe for automatic discovery. We assume that everything within is meant to be included in the distribution.
If ``package_dir[""]`` is not given, but the ``src`` directory exists, this function will set ``package_dir[""] = "src"``.

Try to find all packages and modules under the project root.
Since the ``flat-layout`` is more dangerous in terms of accidentally including extra files/directories, this function is more conservative and will raise an error if multiple packages or modules are found.
This assumes that multi-package dists are uncommon and refuse to support that use case in order to be able to prevent unintended errors.
Try to find the root package that is not a PEP 420 namespace
The packages/modules are the essential contribution of the author. Therefore the name of the distribution can be derived from them.
Fill-in metadata and options that can be automatically derived (from other metadata/options, the file system or conventions)
